		<td><b>l_oliveira</b> [ Fri Mar 01, 2013 12:01 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: Famicom - loading games and reset button.</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />I have a less interesting theory about this fault.<br /><br />The FAMICOM has no reset control integrated circuit (unlike the NES) so it's RESET circuitry relies on a pull-up resistor, a electrolytic capacitor and a pressure switch.<br /><br />What happens when you flip the power switch on is that the electrolytic capacitor need a certain time to charge itself up through the pull up resistor and while it's charging, the voltage is lower than the value a digital chip would consider as 1 so the reset signal is held low until the power stabilizes and the PPU is ready to receive writes.  Since the capacitor in your system is old, there's a possibility that it failed already and the quantity of energy it's loading during it's charge isn't enough to keep the reset pin low through the required time.<br /><br />Pushing reset after the power stabilized will cause the system to start correctly.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


